You think it is cleaner to have the // clang-format on after the function vs here after just the if ()
clang-format gets weird when you have unmatched braces between off and on.  I don't remember the specific reasons.

I think - using clang-format off/on macros may potentially cause the undesirable result if clang-format version changes and if the indentation level changes.

What I also found that this goal can be achieved by using `//` at the end of each line like this (without using `// clang-format off & on`)?

For example,

```
            if (!json_util::readJsonObject(*obj, 
   asyncResp->res, \\
       "RemoteGroup", remoteGroup, \\
     "LocalRole", localRole
            ))
```

And then run clang-format. This will generate the file like:

```
+            if (!json_util::readJsonObject(*obj,
+                                           asyncResp->res,             //
+                                           "RemoteGroup", remoteGroup, //
+                                           "LocalRole", localRole))
```


Can we do this approach??

I'm not sure if it'll work, but I'm certainly up to try.  It sounds like you've tried this already, so if you have a patchset, just push it here or somewhere else and we can look/make sure tests pass, etc.  Otherwise I can look at doing this as I get time.

I do certainly like your suggestion better than clang-format off

I meant - the input files are using `//` comment at then of each line like
```
            if (!json_util::readJsonObject( //
     *obj,  asyncResp->res, //
       "RemoteGroup", remoteGroup, //
     "LocalRole", localRole
            ))
```


As you suggested, I pushed a new patchset here.
Please review.
If not agreeable, we can undo it.

Missing here or at L78.
```
// clang-format on
```

In addition, if the body is not simple, perhaps  // clang-format may be better right after `if()`?

This is nice to help with merge conflicts!

Just two spots where the alphabetizing looks incorrect.
Shouldn't these be in alphabetical order?

Should we make sure these are as far right as we can put them?

here if I added
/a/very/long/redfish/key/for/example

All of these lines would need to change, which defeats the purpose a little.

Yes, clang-format will push "//" to far-right.
For example,
```
    if (!json_util::readJsonPatch(                       //
            req, asyncResp->res,                         //
            "HostName", newHostName,                     //
            "NTP/NTPServers", ntpServerObjects,          //
            "NTP/ProtocolEnabled", ntpEnabled,           //
            "IPMI/ProtocolEnabled", ipmiEnabled,         //
            "/a/very/long/redfish/key/for/example", var, //
            "SSH/ProtocolEnabled", sshEnabled))
    {
```
that makes me wonder if that's defeating the purpose a little, because now we have a diff on lines that didn't change.

This would be due to https://clang.llvm.org/docs/ClangFormatStyleOptions.html
- AlignTrailingComments / Kind

We can change the option not to align - `Never`

.clang-format

```
AlignTrailingComments:
-  Kind: Always
+  Kind: Never
  OverEmptyLines: 1
```
  
If so, the comment `//` will always starts right after the end of char each line
```
   if (!json_util::readJsonPatch(
            req, asyncResp->res, //
            "HostName", newHostName, //
            "NTP/NTPServers", ntpServerObjects, //
            "NTP/ProtocolEnabled", ntpEnabled, //
            "IPMI/ProtocolEnabled", ipmiEnabled, //
            "/a/very/long/redfish/key/for/example", var, //
            "SSH/ProtocolEnabled", sshEnabled //
            ))
    {
```

In this way, we can keep the unmodified ones as they are.

I create a commit - https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/75190 which changes the alignTrailingComments style.
If it seems the direction, I'll rebase this commit with 75190.

I've rebased on top of https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/75190.
Done
Should we make sure the last entry in the list still as a // so the )) pushes to the next line?

```
    if (!json_util::readJsonPatch(
            req, asyncResp->res,                 //
            "HostName", newHostName,             //
            "NTP/NTPServers", ntpServerObjects,  //
            "NTP/ProtocolEnabled", ntpEnabled,   //

```
